:::summary
Constantine the Great (c. AD 272–337) was the first Roman Emperor to embrace Christianity — and the man whose conversion and policies transformed a persecuted minority faith into the official religion of the greatest empire in the Western world. His reign marks one of the most consequential turning points in all of Christian history, shaping the church's institutions, theology, and relationship to political power for the next seventeen centuries.
:::

